## DESCRIPTION
##   Graphing a Function
## ENDDESCRIPTION

## Tagged by nhamblet

## DBsubject(Calculus - single variable)
## DBchapter(Applications of differentiation)
## DBsection(Summary of curve sketching)
## Institution(Rochester)
## MLT(SCS_all_rat)
## Level(3)
## KEYWORDS('Graph', 'Increasing', 'Decreasing', 'Concavity', 'Critical', 'Inflection', 'Asymptote')

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
"PGcourse.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(2,4,2);
$b = random(5,9,2);
$c = random(6,8,2);
$d = random(3,5,2);
## ad-bc always negative
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Consider the function \( \displaystyle f(x) = \frac { $a x + $b } { $c x + $d } \).
$PAR
For this function there are two important intervals:
 \( (-\infty, A) \) and \( (A,\infty) \) where
 the function is not defined at \( A \).
 $BR
Find \( A \): \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = -$d/$c;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR Find the horizontal asymptote of \( f(x) \): $BR
\(y=\) \{ans_rule(10) \} 
EOT
$ans = $a/$c;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR Find the vertical asymptote of \( f(x) \): $BR
\(x=\) \{ans_rule(10) \} 
EOT
$ans = -$d/$c;
ANS(num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR
For each of the following intervals, tell whether \( f(x) \)
is increasing (type in INC) or decreasing (type in DEC).
$BR
 \( (-\infty, A) \): \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = "DEC";
ANS(num_cmp($ans, strings=>['INC','DEC']));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR
\( (A,\infty) \): \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = "DEC";
ANS(num_cmp($ans, strings=>['INC','DEC']));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR
Note that this function has no inflection points, but we can still consider its concavity.
For each of the following intervals, tell whether \( f(x) \)
is concave up (type in CU) or concave down (type in CD).
$BR
 \( (-\infty, A) \): \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = "CD";
ANS(num_cmp($ans, strings=>['CU','CD']));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
\( (A,\infty) \): \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = "CU";
ANS(num_cmp($ans, strings=>['CU','CD']));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$PAR
Sketch the graph of \(f(x)\) and bring it to class.
EOT

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
